# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __invert__, __floor__, __ceil__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __invert__: false for all 10 — bitwise inversion is not defined for any type.
# __floor__: false for all 10 — numeric floor is not defined for any type.
# __ceil__: false for all 10 — numeric ceiling is not defined for any type.
# All 30 values are false.
# asyncio types are designed for coroutine-based concurrency — their entire
#   API surface is expressed through await, async with, async for, and explicit
#   method calls. No numeric data model protocol is implemented: waves 658–670
#   established that all arithmetic (__add__/__sub__/__mul__), division
#   (__truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__), power/shift, bitwise logical, reflected
#   arithmetic, reflected bitwise, in-place augmented assignment, and unary
#   numeric operators (__neg__/__pos__/__abs__) are absent from all 10 asyncio
#   types. The integer inversion and rounding operators tested here follow the
#   same pattern.
# asyncio.Event note: Event manages a simple boolean flag (set/clear/wait);
#   integer bitwise inversion and rounding have no meaning for a two-state guard.
# asyncio.Lock/Condition note: mutual-exclusion synchronization objects;
#   there is no numeric state to invert or round.
# asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore note: the permit counter is encapsulated
#   and not exposed through any numeric data model method, including __invert__,
#   __floor__, or __ceil__.
# asyncio.Queue note: Queue is an ordered item store; items are managed
#   through put()/get() coroutine calls; ~queue, math.floor(queue), and
#   math.ceil(queue) are not defined.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

